            "value": "`About`The ~Futur Konjunktiv II~‚Äîconjugated with ~w√ºrde~ + infinitive‚Äîis German's most versatile conditional construction. It expresses hypothetical, counterfactual, and politely uncertain future actions: what ~would~ happen, what one ~would~ do, what ~would~ be the case if circumstances were different.\n\nThis compound conjugationgroup combines:\n\nüá©üá™ The auxiliary verb ~w√ºrde~ (Pr√§teritum Konjunktiv II of ~werden~)\nüá©üá™ The ~infinitive~ of the main verb\n\nThe result: \"Ich ~w√ºrde~ gern ~helfen~\" (I would gladly help) or \"Er ~w√ºrde~ kommen, wenn er k√∂nnte\" (He would come if he could).\n\nThe ~w√ºrde~-construction has become the dominant way to express conditionality in modern German, especially in speech. While strong verbs retain their synthetic Pr√§teritum Konjunktiv II conjugations (~k√§me~, ~g√§be~, ~s√§he~), weak verbs and many strong verbs now prefer the ~w√ºrde~ + infinitive construction for clarity and ease.`Conjugation`The Futur Konjunktiv II uses ~w√ºrde~ (the Konjunktiv II conjugation of ~werden~) plus the infinitive of the main verb.`Conjugation of w√ºrde`üá©üá™ ich ~w√ºrde~ (I would)\nüá©üá™ du ~w√ºrdest~ (you would)\nüá©üá™ er/sie/es ~w√ºrde~ (he/she/it would)\nüá©üá™ wir ~w√ºrden~ (we would)\nüá©üá™ ihr ~w√ºrdet~ (you all would)\nüá©üá™ sie/Sie ~w√ºrden~ (they/you-formal would)\n\nThese conjugations derive from ~werden~ via the standard Konjunktiv II pattern: Pr√§teritum stem (~wurd-~) + umlaut (~w√ºrd-~) + subjunctive endings.`Complete Examples`üá©üá™ Ich ~w√ºrde~ das Buch ~lesen~. (I would read the book.)\nüá©üá™ Du ~w√ºrdest~ es ~verstehen~. (You would understand it.)\nüá©üá™ Er ~w√ºrde~ gern ~helfen~. (He would gladly help.)\nüá©üá™ Wir ~w√ºrden~ nach Berlin ~fahren~. (We would go to Berlin.)\nüá©üá™ Ihr ~w√ºrdet~ es ~sehen~. (You all would see it.)\nüá©üá™ Sie ~w√ºrden~ zustimmen. (They would agree.)`Word Order`In main clauses, ~w√ºrde~ takes the second position (V2), while the infinitive moves to the end:\n\nüá©üá™ \"Ich ~w√ºrde~ gern morgen ~kommen~.\" = \"I would gladly come tomorrow.\"\nüá©üá™ \"Sie ~w√ºrde~ das nie ~sagen~.\" = \"She would never say that.\"\n\nIn subordinate clauses, both elements move to the end, with the infinitive preceding ~w√ºrde~:\n\nüá©üá™ \"Ich wei√ü, dass er es ~tun w√ºrde~.\" = \"I know that he would do it.\"\nüá©üá™ \"Wenn sie ~kommen w√ºrde~, w√§re ich froh.\" = \"If she would come, I would be happy.\"`Futur Konjunktiv II by Verb Family`The infinitive remains unchanged regardless of verb family‚Äîall the conditional meaning is carried by ~w√ºrde~.`Weak Verbs`üá©üá™ machen ‚Üí ich ~w√ºrde~ ~machen~ (I would make)\nüá©üá™ sagen ‚Üí er ~w√ºrde~ ~sagen~ (he would say)\nüá©üá™ arbeiten ‚Üí wir ~w√ºrden~ ~arbeiten~ (we would work)\nüá©üá™ kaufen ‚Üí sie ~w√ºrden~ ~kaufen~ (they would buy)\n\nFor weak verbs, the ~w√ºrde~-construction is strongly preferred because their synthetic Konjunktiv II conjugations are identical to the Pr√§teritum Indikativ (~machte~, ~sagte~), creating ambiguity.`Strong Verbs`üá©üá™ sehen ‚Üí ich ~w√ºrde~ ~sehen~ (I would see)\nüá©üá™ gehen ‚Üí du ~w√ºrdest~ ~gehen~ (you would go)\nüá©üá™ kommen ‚Üí er ~w√ºrde~ ~kommen~ (he would come)\nüá©üá™ nehmen ‚Üí wir ~w√ºrden~ ~nehmen~ (we would take)\n\nStrong verbs have distinct synthetic Konjunktiv II conjugations (~s√§he~, ~ginge~, ~k√§me~, ~n√§hme~), but the ~w√ºrde~-construction is increasingly common in colloquial German.`Separable-Prefix Verbs`Separable prefixes remain attached to the infinitive:\n\nüá©üá™ ankommen ‚Üí ich ~w√ºrde~ ~ankommen~ (I would arrive)\nüá©üá™ aufstehen ‚Üí du ~w√ºrdest~ ~aufstehen~ (you would get up)\nüá©üá™ mitnehmen ‚Üí er ~w√ºrde~ ~mitnehmen~ (he would take along)`w√ºrde vs. Synthetic Konjunktiv II Conjugations`German has two ways to express conditionality: the synthetic conjugations (Pr√§teritum Konjunktiv II) and the analytic ~w√ºrde~-construction. How do they differ?\n\n~Synthetic conjugations~ (k√§me, g√§be, s√§he, etc.):\nü™∂ More formal and literary\nüí™ Preferred for high-frequency verbs: ~w√§re~, ~h√§tte~, ~k√∂nnte~, ~m√ºsste~, ~sollte~, ~wollte~\n‚õ∞Ô∏è Common in southern German dialects\nü§î Required for ~sein~, ~haben~, and modal verbs in careful usage\n\n~w√ºrde + infinitive~:\nüéÇ More colloquial and widespread\nü§ì Strongly preferred for weak verbs (avoids Pr√§teritum/Konjunktiv II ambiguity)\nüéôÔ∏è Increasingly common even for strong verbs in speech\nüêã Universal fallback when synthetic conjugation is unknown or awkward\n\nIn practice, both constructions coexist. A sentence like \"Wenn ich reich ~w√§re~, ~w√ºrde~ ich ein Haus ~kaufen~\" uses the synthetic ~w√§re~ for ~sein~ but the analytic ~w√ºrde kaufen~ for ~kaufen~‚Äîa natural mixing of conjugations.`Usage Contexts:``Hypothetical Conditions`The Futur Konjunktiv II appears in the main clause of unreal conditional sentences:\n\nüá©üá™ \"Wenn ich Zeit h√§tte, ~w√ºrde~ ich dir ~helfen~.\" = \"If I had time, I would help you.\"\nüá©üá™ \"Wenn es nicht regnete, ~w√ºrden~ wir spazieren ~gehen~.\" = \"If it weren't raining, we would go for a walk.\"\nüá©üá™ \"~W√ºrdest~ du ~kommen~, wenn ich dich einlade?\" = \"Would you come if I invited you?\"`Polite Requests and Suggestions`The ~w√ºrde~-construction softens requests:\n\nüá©üá™ \"~W√ºrden~ Sie mir bitte ~helfen~?\" = \"Would you please help me?\"\nüá©üá™ \"Ich ~w√ºrde~ vorschlagen, dass wir fr√ºher anfangen.\" = \"I would suggest that we start earlier.\"\nüá©üá™ \"~W√ºrdest~ du das Fenster ~√∂ffnen~?\" = \"Would you open the window?\"`Wishes and Desires`Expressing what one would like:\n\nüá©üá™ \"Ich ~w√ºrde~ gern nach Japan ~reisen~.\" = \"I would like to travel to Japan.\"\nüá©üá™ \"Er ~w√ºrde~ lieber zu Hause ~bleiben~.\" = \"He would rather stay home.\"\nüá©üá™ \"Wir ~w√ºrden~ uns freuen, Sie wiederzusehen.\" = \"We would be pleased to see you again.\"`Reported Conditional`Expressing what someone would do according to report:\n\nüá©üá™ \"Er sagte, er ~w√ºrde~ uns ~helfen~.\" = \"He said he would help us.\"\nüá©üá™ \"Sie meinte, sie ~w√ºrde~ sp√§ter ~anrufen~.\" = \"She said she would call later.\"` Differences from English`The German ~w√ºrde~-construction parallels English \"would\" closely, but some differences exist:\n\nüá©üá™/üè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å•Û†ÅÆÛ†ÅßÛ†Åø ~Competition with synthetic conjugations~: German retains synthetic Konjunktiv II conjugations (~k√§me~, ~w√§re~) that compete with the analytic construction. English \"would\" has no such competitor for most verbs.\nüá©üá™/üè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å•Û†ÅÆÛ†ÅßÛ†Åø ~Weak-verb preference~: German strongly prefers ~w√ºrde~ for weak verbs because their synthetic conjugations are ambiguous. English has no parallel concern.\nüá©üá™/üè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å•Û†ÅÆÛ†ÅßÛ†Åø ~Auxiliary exceptions~: German still strongly prefers ~w√§re~, ~h√§tte~, and modal Konjunktiv II conjugations over ~w√ºrde sein~, ~w√ºrde haben~, etc. English uses \"would be,\" \"would have\" freely.\nüá©üá™/üè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å•Û†ÅÆÛ†ÅßÛ†Åø ~Politeness marking~: German ~w√ºrde~ conjugations are more explicitly marked as polite/conditional than English \"would,\" which has broader uses (habitual past: \"He would always arrive late\").`Historical Development`The ~w√ºrde~-construction emerged in Middle High German (c. 1050‚Äì1350) as an alternative to synthetic subjunctive conjugations. The verb ~werden~ had long meant \"to become,\" and its subjunctive (~w√ºrde~) began combining with infinitives to express futurity and conditionality.\n\nBy Early New High German (c. 1350‚Äì1650), the construction was well established, especially for weak verbs whose synthetic Konjunktiv II conjugations had merged with the Pr√§teritum Indikativ. The pattern ~ich w√ºrde machen~ provided an unambiguous conditional alternative to ~ich machte~ (which could mean \"I made\" or \"I would make\").\n\nOver the following centuries, the ~w√ºrde~-construction expanded steadily, displacing synthetic conjugations even for many strong verbs in colloquial speech. Today, it serves as the default conditional for all but the most common verbs‚Äîa grammaticalization process that transformed \"would become\" into a pure conditional marker.`Literary Examples`The Futur Konjunktiv II appears throughout German literature for hypothetical reasoning, polite suggestion, and contrary-to-fact imagination.`Goethe ‚Äî The Sorrows of Young Werther (1774)`\"Ich ~w√ºrde~ sagen: du bist ein Tor! Du suchst, was hienieden nicht zu finden ist!\" = \"I would say: you are a fool! You seek what is not to be found here below!\"\n\nWerther imagines what he ~would~ say to himself‚Äîa self-critical hypothetical. The ~w√ºrde sagen~ frames the accusation as a judgment he might pass, not one he fully accepts.\n\n\"H√§tte er gewartet, bis seine Kr√§fte sich erholt, alles ~w√§re~ gut ~gegangen~.\" = \"Had he waited until his strength was restored, all ~would~ have ~gone~ well.\"\n\nAlbert's argument about suicide uses the Konjunktiv II (~w√§re gegangen~) to express a counterfactual outcome‚Äîwhat ~would~ have happened if the patient had acted differently. Here the synthetic conjugation appears rather than ~w√ºrde~.`Kafka ‚Äî The Trial (1925)`\"~W√ºrde~ man ihm nicht glauben, so konnte er Frau Grubach als Zeugin f√ºhren.\" = \"Should they not believe him, he could call Mrs. Grubach as a witness.\"\n\nK.'s contingency planning uses ~w√ºrde~ to set up a hypothetical scenario: if they ~would~ not believe him, then a backup plan exists.\n\n\"Wollte er einen andern Termin w√ºnschen, so ~w√ºrde~ man ihm, so gut es ginge, ~entgegenkommen~.\" = \"Should he wish a different time, they ~would~ accommodate him as best they could.\"\n\nThe court's message uses ~w√ºrde entgegenkommen~ to express conditional willingness‚Äîa promise contingent on K.'s wishes.`Mann ‚Äî Death in Venice (1912)`\"H√§tte er sie ein wenig zur√ºckbehalten, h√§tte er es auf den Versuch einer Anpassung ankommen lassen, so ~w√ºrde~ ihm ein Vormittag am Strande ~bevorstehen~.\" = \"Had he held back a bit, had he allowed himself to try adapting, a morning on the beach ~would~ await him.\"\n\nMann's elaborate counterfactual uses ~w√ºrde bevorstehen~ in the main clause‚Äîwhat ~would~ have been the result of a different choice. The contrary-to-fact condition imagines an alternative to Aschenbach's departure from Venice.`Why the Futur Konjunktiv II Matters`The Futur Konjunktiv II is essential for:\n\nüá©üá™ ~Everyday politeness~: \"~W√ºrden~ Sie mir bitte helfen?\" is standard polite German.\nüá©üá™ ~Hypothetical discussion~: Debating what ~would~ happen, what one ~would~ do.\nüá©üá™ ~Weak-verb conditionality~: The ~w√ºrde~-construction provides unambiguous conditional meaning where synthetic conjugations are ambiguous.\nüá©üá™ ~Universal fallback~: When you don't know or can't recall a synthetic Konjunktiv II conjugation, ~w√ºrde~ + infinitive is always correct.\n\nMastering the Futur Konjunktiv II means mastering the most productive conditional pattern in modern German. While purists may prefer ~k√§me~ to ~w√ºrde kommen~, the analytic construction is grammatically impeccable and universally understood. It is the Swiss Army knife of German conditionality‚Äîalways available, always clear, always correct."
