        "en": {
          "stringUnit": {
            "state": "translated",
            "value": "~Mood~ expresses the speaker's attitude toward the action or some other information about the action not involving tense or voice.\n\nLike tense, mood is one component of many conjugationgroups. For example, %Pr√§sens Indikativ% has Pr√§sens tense, implied Aktiv voice, and Indikativ mood.\n\nEnglish-speaking German learners might benefit from identification of the English moods, so here they are:\n\nüè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å•Û†ÅÆÛ†ÅßÛ†Åø ~Indicative~: This mood expresses no attitude and is the default, most widely used mood. Example: \"The indicative mood ~expresses~ no attitude.\"\nüè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å•Û†ÅÆÛ†ÅßÛ†Åø ~Subjunctive~: This mood, largely avoided in informal English, expresses wishes, demands, unreality, or hypotheticality. Examples: \"The low temperature necessitates that the skier ~wear~ a hat.\" \"If I ~were~ a humpback whale, I would divide my time between Hawai ªi and Alaska.\"\nüè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å•Û†ÅÆÛ†ÅßÛ†Åø ~Conditional~: This mood expresses contingency. Example: \"In the absence of other constraints, Josh Adams ~would spend~ every waking hour on development of ~Konjugieren~.\"\nüè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å•Û†ÅÆÛ†ÅßÛ†Åø ~Imperative~: This mood expresses a command. Example: \"Let's conjugate some verbs.\"\n\nGerman mood names differ somewhat from English mood names, but the uses are quite similar.\n\nüá©üá™ ~Indikativ~: This mood states facts and describes reality, just like English indicative. Example: \"Die Katze ~sitzt~ auf der Tastatur‚Äîschon wieder.\" = \"The cat ~is sitting~ on the keyboard‚Äîagain.\"\nüá©üá™ ~Konjunktiv I~: This mood is primarily used for indirect speech (~indirekte Rede~)‚Äîreporting what someone else said. Unlike English, which shifts reported speech into past tense, German preserves the original tense but changes the conjugation. Example: Direct: \"Ich war das nicht.\" ‚Üí Indirect: \"Das Kind sagte, es ~sei~ das nicht gewesen.\" = \"The child said it ~wasn't~ him.\" Konjunktiv I appears mainly in journalism and formal writing. When Konjunktiv I conjugations are identical to indicative, which happens in 1s, 1p, and 3p, speakers substitute Konjunktiv II to maintain clarity.\nüá©üá™ ~Konjunktiv II~, also called ~Konjunktiv II~: This mood expresses hypothetical or contrary-to-fact situations, like English conditional. Example: \"Wenn ich unsichtbar ~w√§re~, ~w√ºrde~ ich trotzdem in der Schlange warten.\" = \"If I ~were~ invisible, I ~would~ still wait in line.\"\nüá©üá™ ~Imperativ~: This mood expresses commands, just like English imperative. Example: \"~Iss~ deinen Brokkoli!\" = \"~Eat~ your broccoli!\"\n\nHere are the German conjugationgroups arranged by mood:\n\nüá©üá™ ~Indikativ~: %Pr√§sens Indikativ%, %Pr√§teritum Indikativ%, %Perfekt Indikativ%\nüá©üá™ ~Konjunktiv I~: %Pr√§sens Konjunktiv I%, %Perfekt Konjunktiv I%\nüá©üá™ ~Konjunktiv II~: %Pr√§teritum Konjunktiv II%\nüá©üá™ ~Imperativ~: %Imperativ%"
